==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|handful||handful|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|handfullan|lang=gem-pro}}, {{recons|handfullō|lang=gem-pro}}, {{recons|handfulljô||handful|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|handuz||hand|lang=gem-pro}}, {{recons|fullaz||full|lang=gem-pro}}, equivalent to {{compound|hand|full|t2=fullness, plenty}}. Cognate with {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|hânfol||handful|lang=fy}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|handvol||handful|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|håndfuld||handful|lang=da}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|handfull||handfull|lang=sv}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|handfylli||handful|lang=is}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en-us-handful.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{IPA|/ˈhæn(d)fʊl/|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|pl2=handsful}}

# As much as the [[hand]] will grasp or contain. - [[w:Joseph Addison|Joseph Addison]]
# {{obsolete}} A hand's [[breadth]]; four [[inch]]es.
#: ''Knap the tongs together about a '''handful''' from the bottom. - [[w:Francis Bacon|Francis Bacon]]
# A small quantity, usually approximately equal to five, the number of fingers on a hand.
#: ''This '''handful''' of men were tied to very hard duty. - [[Fuller]]
# Something which can only be [[manage]]d with difficulty.
#: ''Those twins are a real '''handful''' to look after.

====Synonyms====
* (content of a hand) [[fistful]]
